        <details class="pf-faq-item"><summary><span class="pf-faq-tag pf-tag-green">COMPRESSION</span>&nbsp; What is a compression fitting and why do they fail in older Aintree properties?</summary><div class="pf-faq-body"><p>A compression fitting joins copper pipes using a metal ring called an olive that is compressed by tightening a nut. They are reliable when correctly installed but over decades of thermal expansion and contraction, the olive can deform and the joint begins to weep. In 1970s Aintree properties with original compression fittings, this is a common failure mode. The fix is to cut out the old fitting and install a new one   a straightforward repair that takes less than an hour in most cases.</p></div></details>
